    "narrative": "The offensive outlook for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on a high-upside core facing Lance McCullers Jr., whose susceptibility to basestealing threats makes **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (76.59) and **Giancarlo Stanton** (65.69) primary targets. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** carries the highest daily ceiling as he benefits from a rare combination of strong SP-skill metrics and a favorable matchup for his speed profile against a slow-delivering pitcher. While **Trevor Story** (73.82) holds the highest raw efficiency outside of our leadoff hitters, his surge is driven primarily by a +16% park adjustment that makes him our most potent asset in the UTIL slot today. Meanwhile, **James Wood** (75.23) and **Mickey Moniak** (63.92) anchor the outfield with elite leadoff-spot advantages, with **Mickey Moniak** specifically thriving due to a massive +14% platoon boost against a right-handed starter.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Seiya Suzuki** (44.34), who hovered near the \"Strong\" threshold but ultimately fell short due to the high-efficiency baseline of our starters and the uncertainty surrounding his pending lineup slot. Despite a decent projected base, the optimizer favored **Tyler Soderstrom** (50.66) and **Alex Freeland** (49.29) due to their solidified roles in the order, even as they contend with tough arms like Nathan Eovaldi and Jameson Taillon. We are proceeding with extreme caution regarding **Brice Turang** (48.20), whose score has been suppressed by the elite defensive capabilities of the opposing catcher (1.89s pop time) and the presence of Paul Skenes on the mound. While we need **Brice Turang** for his speed, he remains a high-risk play today, and we have opted to sit **Max Muncy** (38.45) entirely, as his sub-40 efficiency score falls below the Ghost Ride the WHIP bench threshold for a forced start.",
